# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: general-relativity-numerics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] The **Arnowitt–Deser–Misner** (**ADM**) **formalism** (named for its authors Richard Arnowitt, Stanley Deser and Charles W.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] Misner) is a Hamiltonian formulation of general relativity that plays an important role in canonical quantum gravity and numerical relativity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] The comprehensive review of the formalism that the authors published in 1962 has been reprinted in the journal *General Relativity and Gravitation*, while the original papers can be found in the archives of *Physical Review*.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] The formalism supposes that spacetime is foliated into a family of spacelike surfaces ⁠ $\Sigma _{t}$ ⁠, labeled by their time coordinate ⁠ t ⁠, and with coordinates on each slice given by ⁠ $x^{i}$ ⁠.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] The dynamic variables of this theory are taken to be the metric tensor of three-dimensional spatial slices ⁠ $\gamma _{ij}(t,x^{k})$ ⁠ and their conjugate momenta ⁠ $\pi ^{ij}(t,x^{k})$ ⁠.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] Using these variables it is possible to define a Hamiltonian, and thereby write the equations of motion for general relativity in the form of Hamilton's equations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] In addition to the twelve variables ⁠ $\gamma _{ij}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\pi ^{ij}$ ⁠, there are four Lagrange multipliers: the lapse function, ⁠ N ⁠, and components of shift vector field, ⁠ $N_{i}$ ⁠.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] These describe how each of the "leaves" ⁠ $\Sigma _{t}$ ⁠ of the foliation of spacetime are welded together.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] The equations of motion for these variables can be freely specified; this freedom corresponds to the freedom to specify how to lay out the coordinate system in space and time.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] Most references adopt notation in which four dimensional tensors are written in abstract index notation, and that Greek indices are spacetime indices taking values (0, 1, 2, 3) and Latin indices are spatial indices taking values (1, 2, 3).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] In the derivation here, a superscript (4) is prepended to quantities that typically have both a three-dimensional and a four-dimensional version, such as the metric tensor for three-dimensional slices $g_{ij}$ and the metric tensor for the full four-dimensional spacetime ${^{(4)}}g_{\mu \nu }$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] The text here uses Einstein notation in which summation over repeated indices is assumed.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] Two types of derivatives are used: Partial derivatives are denoted either by the operator $\partial _{i}$ or by subscripts preceded by a comma.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] Covariant derivatives are denoted either by the operator $\nabla _{i}$ or by subscripts preceded by a semicolon.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] The absolute value of the determinant of the matrix of metric tensor coefficients is represented by g (with no indices).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] Other tensor symbols written without indices represent the trace of the corresponding tensor such as $\pi =g^{ij}\pi _{ij}$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] The **ADM split** denotes the separation of the spacetime metric into three spatial components and one temporal component (foliation).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] The basic idea is to express the spacetime metric in terms of a lapse function that represents the time evolution between hypersurfaces, and a shift vector that represents spatial coordinate changes between these hypersurfaces) along with a 3D spatial metric.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] where N is the lapse function encoding the proper time evolution, $N_{i}$ is the shift vector, encoding how spatial coordinates change between hypersurfaces. $g_{ij}$ is the emergent 3D spatial metric on each hypersurface.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] This decomposition allows for a separation of the spacetime evolution equations into constraints (which relate the initial data on a spatial hypersurface) and evolution equations (which describe how the geometry of spacetime changes from one hypersurface to another).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] which is a product of the square root of the determinant of the four-dimensional metric tensor for the full spacetime and its Ricci scalar.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] This is the Lagrangian from the Einstein–Hilbert action.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] The desired outcome of the derivation is to define an embedding of three-dimensional spatial slices in the four-dimensional spacetime.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] will be the generalized coordinates for a Hamiltonian formulation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] using standard techniques and definitions.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] The symbols ${^{(4)}}\Gamma _{ij}^{0}$ are Christoffel symbols associated with the metric of the full four-dimensional spacetime.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] are the remaining elements of the four-metric tensor.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] Having identified the quantities for the formulation, the next step is to rewrite the Lagrangian in terms of these variables.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] which are known as the Hamiltonian constraint and the momentum constraint respectively.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] The lapse and the shift appear in the Lagrangian as Lagrange multipliers.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] is a non-linear set of partial differential equations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] and the lapse and shift themselves can be freely specified, reflecting the fact that coordinate systems can be freely specified in both space and time.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] Using the ADM formulation, it is possible to attempt to construct a quantum theory of gravity in the same way that one constructs the Schrödinger equation corresponding to a given Hamiltonian in quantum mechanics.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] More precisely, the replacing of classical variables by operators is restricted by commutation relations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] The hats represent operators in quantum theory.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] This leads to the Wheeler–DeWitt equation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] There are relatively few known exact solutions to the Einstein field equations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] In order to find other solutions, there is an active field of study known as numerical relativity in which supercomputers are used to find approximate solutions to the equations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] In order to construct such solutions numerically, most researchers start with a formulation of the Einstein equations closely related to the ADM formulation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] The most common approaches start with an initial value problem based on the ADM formalism.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] In Hamiltonian formulations, the basic point is replacement of set of second order equations by another first order set of equations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] We may get this second set of equations by Hamiltonian formulation in an easy way.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] Of course this is very useful for numerical physics, because reducing the order of differential equations is often convenient if we want to prepare equations for a computer.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] ADM energy is a special way to define the energy in general relativity, which is only applicable to some special geometries of spacetime that asymptotically approach a well-defined metric tensor at infinity – for example a spacetime that asymptotically approaches Minkowski space.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] The ADM energy in these cases is defined as a function of the deviation of the metric tensor from its prescribed asymptotic form.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] In other words, the ADM energy is computed as the strength of the gravitational field at infinity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] If the required asymptotic form is time-independent (such as the Minkowski space itself), then it respects the time-translational symmetry.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] Noether's theorem then implies that the ADM energy is conserved.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] According to general relativity, the conservation law for the total energy does not hold in more general, time-dependent backgrounds – for example, it is completely violated in physical cosmology.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] Cosmic inflation in particular is able to produce energy (and mass) from "nothing" because the vacuum energy density is roughly constant, but the volume of the Universe grows exponentially.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/adm-formalism] By using the ADM decomposition and introducing extra auxiliary fields, in 2009 Deruelle et al. found a method to find the Gibbons–Hawking–York boundary term for modified gravity theories "whose Lagrangian is an arbitrary function of the Riemann tensor".
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] In mathematics and physics, the **Christoffel symbols** are an array of numbers describing a metric connection.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The metric connection is a specialization of the affine connection to surfaces or other manifolds endowed with a metric, allowing distances to be measured on that surface.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] In differential geometry, an affine connection can be defined without reference to a metric, and many additional concepts follow: parallel transport, covariant derivatives, geodesics, etc. also do not require the concept of a metric.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] However, when a metric is available, these concepts can be directly tied to the "shape" of the manifold itself; that shape is determined by how the tangent space is attached to the cotangent space by the metric tensor.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Abstractly, one would say that the manifold has an associated (orthonormal) frame bundle, with each "frame" being a possible choice of a coordinate frame.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] An invariant metric implies that the structure group of the frame bundle is the orthogonal group O(*p*, *q*).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] As a result, such a manifold is necessarily a (pseudo-)Riemannian manifold.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The Christoffel symbols provide a concrete representation of the connection of (pseudo-)Riemannian geometry in terms of coordinates on the manifold.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Additional concepts, such as parallel transport, geodesics, etc. can then be expressed in terms of Christoffel symbols.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] In general, there are an infinite number of metric connections for a given metric tensor; however, there is a unique connection that is free of torsion, the Levi-Civita connection.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] It is common in physics and general relativity to work almost exclusively with the Levi-Civita connection, by working in coordinate frames (called holonomic coordinates) where the torsion vanishes.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] For example, in Euclidean spaces, the Christoffel symbols describe how the local coordinate bases change from point to point.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] At each point of the underlying *n*-dimensional manifold, for any local coordinate system around that point, the Christoffel symbols are denoted Γ*i**jk* for *i*, *j*, *k* = 1, 2, ..., *n*.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Each entry of this *n* × *n* × *n* array is a real number.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Under *linear* coordinate transformations on the manifold, the Christoffel symbols transform like the components of a tensor, but under general coordinate transformations (diffeomorphisms) they do not.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Most of the algebraic properties of the Christoffel symbols follow from their relationship to the affine connection; only a few follow from the fact that the structure group is the orthogonal group O(*m*, *n*) (or the Lorentz group O(3, 1) for general relativity).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Christoffel symbols are used for performing practical calculations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] For example, the Riemann curvature tensor can be expressed entirely in terms of the Christoffel symbols and their first partial derivatives.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] In general relativity, the connection plays the role of the gravitational force field with the corresponding gravitational potential being the metric tensor.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] When the coordinate system and the metric tensor share some symmetry, many of the Γ*i**jk* are zero.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The Christoffel symbols are named for Elwin Bruno Christoffel (1829–1900).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The definitions given below are valid for both Riemannian manifolds and pseudo-Riemannian manifolds, such as those of general relativity, with careful distinction being made between upper and lower indices (contra-variant and co-variant indices).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The formulas hold for either sign convention, unless otherwise noted.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Einstein summation convention is used in this article, with vectors indicated by bold font.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The **connection coefficients** of the Levi-Civita connection (or pseudo-Riemannian connection) expressed in a coordinate basis are called *Christoffel symbols*.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Given a manifold M , an atlas consists of a collection of charts $\varphi :U\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ for each open cover $U\subset M$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Such charts allow the standard vector basis $({\vec {e}}_{1},\cdots ,{\vec {e}}_{n})$ on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ to be pulled back to a vector basis on the tangent space $TM$ of M .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] This gradient is commonly called a pullback because it "pulls back" the gradient on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ to a gradient on M .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The pullback is independent of the chart $\varphi$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] In this way, the standard vector basis $({\vec {e}}_{1},\cdots ,{\vec {e}}_{n})$ on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ pulls back to a standard ("coordinate") vector basis $(\partial _{1},\cdots ,\partial _{n})$ on $TM$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] This is called the "coordinate basis", because it explicitly depends on the coordinates on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] It is sometimes called the "local basis".
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] This definition allows a common abuse of notation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The $\partial _{i}$ were defined to be in one-to-one correspondence with the basis vectors ${\vec {e}}_{i}$ on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The notation $\partial _{i}$ serves as a reminder that the basis vectors on the tangent space $TM$ came from a gradient construction.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Despite this, it is common to "forget" this construction, and just write (or rather, define) vectors $e_{i}$ on $TM$ such that $e_{i}\equiv \partial _{i}$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] where $\equiv$ is used as a reminder that these are defined to be equivalent notation for the same concept.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The choice of notation is according to style and taste, and varies from text to text.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The coordinate basis provides a vector basis for vector fields on M .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The upper-case X , without the vector-arrow, is particularly popular for index-free notation, because it both minimizes clutter and reminds that results are independent of the chosen basis, and, in this case, independent of the atlas.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The same abuse of notation is used to push forward one-forms from $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ to M .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The one-form is then $dx^{i}=d\varphi ^{i}$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] This is soldered to the basis vectors as $dx^{i}(\partial _{j})=\delta _{j}^{i}$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Note the careful use of upper and lower indexes, to distinguish contravariant and covariant vectors.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The pullback induces (defines) a metric tensor on M .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Several styles of notation are commonly used: $g_{ij}=\mathbf {e} _{i}\cdot \mathbf {e} _{j}=\langle {\vec {e}}_{i},{\vec {e}}_{j}\rangle =e_{i}^{a}e_{j}^{b}\,\eta _{ab}$ where both the centerdot and the angle-bracket $\langle ,\rangle$ denote the scalar product.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The last form uses the tensor $\eta _{ab}$ , which is understood to be the "flat-space" metric tensor.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] For Riemannian manifolds, it is the Kronecker delta $\eta _{ab}=\delta _{ab}$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] For pseudo-Riemannian manifolds, it is the diagonal matrix having signature $(p,q)$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The notation $e_{i}^{a}$ serves as a reminder that pullback really is a linear transform, given as the gradient, above.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The index letters $a,b,c,\cdots$ live in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ while the index letters $i,j,k,\cdots$ live in the tangent manifold.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Some texts write $\mathbf {g} _{i}$ for $\mathbf {e} _{i}$ , so that the metric tensor takes the particularly beguiling form $g_{ij}=\mathbf {g} _{i}\cdot \mathbf {g} _{j}$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] This is commonly done so that the symbol $e_{i}$ can be used unambiguously for the vierbein.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] In words, the arrays represented by the Christoffel symbols track how the basis changes from point to point.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] If the derivative does not lie on the tangent space, the right expression is the projection of the derivative over the tangent space (see covariant derivative below).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Symbols of the second kind decompose the change with respect to the basis, while symbols of the first kind decompose it with respect to the dual basis.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The Christoffel symbols come in two forms: the first kind, and the second kind.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The definition of the second kind is more basic, and thus is presented first.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The Christoffel symbols of the second kind are the connection coefficients—in a coordinate basis—of the Levi-Civita connection.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] As a shorthand notation, the nabla symbol and the partial derivative symbols are frequently dropped, and instead a semicolon and a comma are used to set off the index that is being used for the derivative.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] where (*gjk*) is the inverse of the matrix (*gjk*), defined as (using the Kronecker delta, and Einstein notation for summation) $g^{ji}g_{ik}=\delta ^{j}{}_{k}$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Although the Christoffel symbols are written in the same notation as tensors with index notation, they do not transform like tensors under a change of coordinates.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Contracting the upper index with either of the lower indices (those being symmetric) leads to ${\Gamma ^{i}}_{ki}={\frac {\partial }{\partial x^{k}}}\ln {\sqrt {|g|}}$ where $g=\det g_{ik}$ is the determinant of the metric tensor.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] This identity can be used to evaluate the divergence of vectors and the covariant derivatives of tensor densities.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The Christoffel symbols are most typically defined in a coordinate basis, which is the convention followed here.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] In other words, the name **Christoffel symbols** is reserved only for coordinate (i.e., holonomic) frames.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] where **u***k* are the basis vectors and [ , ] is the Lie bracket.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The standard unit vectors in spherical and cylindrical coordinates furnish an example of a basis with non-vanishing commutation coefficients.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The difference between the connection in such a frame, and the Levi-Civita connection is known as the contorsion tensor.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] In this case, the connection coefficients *ωabc* are called the **Ricci rotation coefficients**.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Equivalently, one can define Ricci rotation coefficients as follows: ${\omega ^{k}}_{ij}:=\mathbf {u} ^{k}\cdot \left(\nabla _{j}\mathbf {u} _{i}\right)\,,$ where **u***i* is an orthonormal nonholonomic basis and **u***k* = *ηkl***u***l* its *co-basis*.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] where the overline denotes the Christoffel symbols in the ${\bar {x}}^{i}$ coordinate system.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The Christoffel symbol does **not** transform as a tensor, but rather as an object in the jet bundle.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] More precisely, the Christoffel symbols can be considered as functions on the jet bundle of the frame bundle of *M*, independent of any local coordinate system.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Choosing a local coordinate system determines a local section of this bundle, which can then be used to pull back the Christoffel symbols to functions on *M*, though of course these functions then depend on the choice of local coordinate system.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] For each point, there exist coordinate systems in which the Christoffel symbols vanish at the point.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] These are called (geodesic) normal coordinates, and are often used in Riemannian geometry.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] There are some interesting properties which can be derived directly from the transformation law.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Now just by using the condition that the scalar product $g_{ik}\xi ^{i}\eta ^{k}$ formed by two arbitrary vectors $\xi ^{i}$ and $\eta ^{k}$ is unchanged is enough to derive the Christoffel symbols.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] This is same as the equation obtained by requiring the covariant derivative of the metric tensor to vanish in the General definition section.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] By cyclically permuting the indices $ikl$ in above equation, we can obtain two more equations and then linearly combining these three equations, we can express ${\Gamma ^{i}}_{jk}$ in terms of the metric tensor.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Let *X* and *Y* be vector fields with components *Xi* and *Yk*.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Keep in mind that *gik* ≠ *gik* and that *gik* = *δ ik*, the Kronecker delta.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The convention is that the metric tensor is the one with the lower indices; the correct way to obtain *gik* from *gik* is to solve the linear equations *gijgjk* = *δ ik*.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The index-less transformation properties of a tensor are given by pullbacks for covariant indices, and pushforwards for contravariant indices.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The article on covariant derivatives provides additional discussion of the correspondence between index-free notation and indexed notation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The symmetry of the Christoffel symbol now implies $\nabla _{i}\nabla _{j}\varphi =\nabla _{j}\nabla _{i}\varphi$ for any scalar field, but in general the covariant derivatives of higher order tensor fields do not commute (see curvature tensor).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The Christoffel symbols find frequent use in Einstein's theory of general relativity, where spacetime is represented by a curved 4-dimensional Lorentz manifold with a Levi-Civita connection.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The Einstein field equations—which determine the geometry of spacetime in the presence of matter—contain the Ricci tensor, and so calculating the Christoffel symbols is essential.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Once the geometry is determined, the paths of particles and light beams are calculated by solving the geodesic equations in which the Christoffel symbols explicitly appear.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Let $x^{i}$ be the generalized coordinates and ${\dot {x}}^{i}$ be the generalized velocities, then the kinetic energy for a unit mass is given by $T={\tfrac {1}{2}}g_{ik}{\dot {x}}^{i}{\dot {x}}^{k}$ , where $g_{ik}$ is the metric tensor.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] If $V\left(x^{i}\right)$ , the potential function, exists then the contravariant components of the generalized force per unit mass are $F_{i}=\partial V/\partial x^{i}$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The metric (here in a purely spatial domain) can be obtained from the line element $ds^{2}=2Tdt^{2}$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] When Cartesian coordinates can be adopted (as in inertial frames of reference), we have an Euclidean metrics, the Christoffel symbol vanishes, and the equation reduces to Newton's second law of motion.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] In curvilinear coordinates (forcedly in non-inertial frames, where the metrics is non-Euclidean and not flat), fictitious forces like the Centrifugal force and Coriolis force originate from the Christoffel symbols, so from the purely spatial curvilinear coordinates.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Given a spherical coordinate system, which describes points on the Earth surface (approximated as an ideal sphere).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] For a point x, R is the distance to the Earth core (usually approximately the Earth radius). θ and φ are the latitude and longitude.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] To simplify the derivatives, the angles are given in radians (where d sin(x)/dx = cos(x), the degree values introduce an additional factor of 360 / 2 pi).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] At any location, the tangent directions are $e_{R}$ (up), $e_{\theta }$ (north) and $e_{\varphi }$ (east) - you can also use indices 1,2,3.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The related metric tensor has only diagonal elements (the squared vector lengths).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] This is an advantage of the coordinate system and not generally true.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Now the necessary quantities can be calculated.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] These values show how the tangent directions (columns: $e_{R}$ , $e_{\theta }$ , $e_{\varphi }$ ) change, seen from an outside perspective (e.g. from space), but given in the tangent directions of the actual location (rows: R, θ, φ).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] These effects are maybe not apparent during the movement, because they are the adjustments that keep the measurements in the coordinates R, θ, φ.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Nevertheless, it can affect distances, physics equations, etc.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] So if e.g. you need the exact change of a magnetic field pointing approximately "south", it can be necessary to also correct your measurement by the change of the north direction using the Christoffel symbols to get the "true" (tensor) value.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Incorporating Lagrangian mechanics and using the Euler–Lagrange equation, Christoffel symbols can be substituted into the Lagrangian to account for the geometry of the manifold.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] Christoffel symbols being calculated from the metric tensor, the equations can be derived and expressed from the principle of least action.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] When applying the Euler-Lagrange equation to a system of equations, the Lagrangian will include terms involving the Christoffel symbols, allowing the equation to act for the curvature which can determine the correct equations of motion for objects moving along geodesics.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/christoffel-symbols] The differential equation provides the mathematical conditions that must be satisfied for this optimal path.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] In the general theory of relativity, the **Einstein field equations** (**EFE**; also known as **Einstein's equations**) relate the geometry of spacetime to the distribution of matter-energy within it.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The equations were published by Albert Einstein in 1915 in the form of a tensor equation which related the local *spacetime curvature* (expressed by the Einstein tensor) with the local energy, momentum and stress within that spacetime (expressed by the stress–energy tensor).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The relationship between the metric tensor and the Einstein tensor allows the EFE to be written as a set of nonlinear partial differential equations when used in this way.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The solutions of the EFE are the components of the metric tensor.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The inertial trajectories of particles and radiation (geodesics) in the resulting geometry are then calculated using the geodesic equation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] As well as implying local energy–momentum conservation, the EFE reduce to Newton's law of gravitation in the limit of a weak gravitational field and velocities that are much less than the speed of light.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Exact solutions for the EFE can only be found under simplifying assumptions such as symmetry.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Special classes of exact solutions are most often studied since they model many gravitational phenomena, such as rotating black holes and the expanding universe.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Further simplification is achieved in approximating the spacetime as having only small deviations from flat spacetime, leading to the linearized EFE.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] These equations are used to study phenomena such as gravitational waves.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] where $G_{\mu \nu }$ is the Einstein tensor, $g_{\mu \nu }$ is the metric tensor, $T_{\mu \nu }$ is the stress–energy tensor, $\Lambda$ is the cosmological constant and $\kappa$ is the Einstein gravitational constant.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] where $R_{\mu \nu }$ is the Ricci curvature tensor, and R is the scalar curvature.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] This is a symmetric divergenceless second-degree tensor that depends on only the metric tensor and its first and second derivatives.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] where G is the Newtonian constant of gravitation and c is the speed of light in vacuum.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] In standard units, each term on the left has quantity dimension of L−2.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The expression on the left represents the curvature of spacetime as determined by the metric; the expression on the right represents the stress–energy–momentum content of spacetime.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The EFE can then be interpreted as a set of equations dictating how stress–energy–momentum determines the curvature of spacetime.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] These equations form the core of the mathematical formulation of general relativity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] They readily imply the geodesic equation, which dictates how freely falling test objects move through spacetime.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The EFE is a tensor equation relating a set of symmetric 4 × 4 tensors.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Each tensor has 10 independent components.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The four Bianchi identities reduce the number of independent equations from 10 to 6, leaving the metric with four gauge-fixing degrees of freedom, which correspond to the freedom to choose a coordinate system.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Although the Einstein field equations were initially formulated in the context of a four-dimensional theory, some theorists have explored their consequences in n dimensions.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The equations in contexts outside of general relativity are still referred to as the Einstein field equations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The vacuum field equations (obtained when $T_{\mu \nu }$ is everywhere zero) define Einstein manifolds.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The equations are more complex than they appear.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Given a specified distribution of matter and energy in the form of a stress–energy tensor, the EFE are understood to be equations for the metric tensor $g_{\mu \nu }$ , since both the Ricci tensor and scalar curvature depend on the metric in a complicated nonlinear manner.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] When fully written out, the EFE are a system of ten coupled, nonlinear, hyperbolic-elliptic partial differential equations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The above form of the EFE is the standard established by Misner, Thorne, and Wheeler (MTW).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] With these definitions Misner, Thorne, and Wheeler classify themselves as (+ + +), whereas Weinberg (1972) is (+ − −), Peebles (1980) and Efstathiou et al.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The sign of the cosmological term would change in both these versions if the (+ − − −) metric sign convention is used rather than the MTW (− + + +) metric sign convention adopted here.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Taking the trace with respect to the metric of both sides of the EFE one gets $R-{\frac {D}{2}}R+D\Lambda =\kappa T,$ where D is the spacetime dimension.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Reversing the trace again would restore the original EFE.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The trace-reversed form may be more convenient in some cases (for example, when one is interested in weak-field limit and can replace $g_{\mu \nu }$ in the expression on the right with the Minkowski metric without significant loss of accuracy).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] In the Einstein field equations $G_{\mu \nu }+\Lambda g_{\mu \nu }=\kappa T_{\mu \nu }\,,$ the term containing the cosmological constant $\Lambda$ was absent from the version in which he originally published them.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Einstein then included the term with the cosmological constant to allow for a universe that is not expanding or contracting.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Einstein then abandoned $\Lambda$ , remarking to George Gamow "that the introduction of the cosmological term was the biggest blunder of his life".
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The inclusion of this term does not create inconsistencies.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] For many years the cosmological constant was almost universally assumed to be zero.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] More recent astronomical observations have shown an accelerating expansion of the universe, and to explain this a positive value of $\Lambda$ is needed.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The effect of the cosmological constant is negligible at the scale of a galaxy or smaller.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The existence of a cosmological constant is thus equivalent to the existence of a vacuum energy and a pressure of opposite sign.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] This has led to the terms "cosmological constant" and "vacuum energy" being used interchangeably in general relativity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] which expresses the local conservation of stress–energy.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] This conservation law is a physical requirement.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] With his field equations Einstein ensured that general relativity is consistent with this conservation condition.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The nonlinearity of the EFE distinguishes general relativity from many other fundamental physical theories.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] For example, Maxwell's equations of electromagnetism are linear in the electric and magnetic fields, and charge and current distributions (i.e. the sum of two solutions is also a solution); another example is the Schrödinger equation of quantum mechanics, which is linear in the wavefunction.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The EFE reduce to Newton's law of gravity by using both the weak-field approximation and the low-velocity approximation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The constant G appearing in the EFE is determined by making these two approximations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Applying these simplifying assumptions to the spatial components of the geodesic equation gives ${\frac {d^{2}x^{i}}{dt^{2}}}\approx -\Gamma _{00}^{i}$ where two factors of ${\textstyle {\frac {{\text{d}}t}{{\text{d}}\tau }}}$ have been divided out.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Our assumptions force $\alpha =i$ and the time (0) derivatives to be zero.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] If the energy–momentum tensor $T_{\mu \nu }$ is zero in the region under consideration, then the field equations are also referred to as the vacuum field equations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The solutions to the vacuum field equations are called vacuum solutions.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Flat Minkowski space is the simplest example of a vacuum solution.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Nontrivial examples include the Schwarzschild solution and the Kerr solution.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Manifolds with a vanishing Ricci tensor, $R_{\mu \nu }=0$ , are referred to as Ricci-flat manifolds and manifolds with a Ricci tensor proportional to the metric as Einstein manifolds.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The first equation asserts that the 4-divergence of the 2-form F is zero, and the second that its exterior derivative is zero.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] This is often taken as equivalent to the covariant Maxwell equation from which it is derived.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] However, there are global solutions of the equation that may lack a globally defined potential.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The solutions of the Einstein field equations are metrics of spacetime.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] These metrics describe the structure of the spacetime including the inertial motion of objects in the spacetime.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] As the field equations are non-linear, they cannot always be completely solved (i.e. without making approximations).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] For example, there is no known complete solution for a spacetime with two massive bodies in it (which is a theoretical model of a binary star system, for example).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] However, approximations are usually made in these cases.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] These are commonly referred to as post-Newtonian approximations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Even so, there are several cases where the field equations have been solved completely, and those are called exact solutions.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The study of exact solutions of Einstein's field equations is one of the activities of cosmology.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] It leads to the prediction of black holes and to different models of evolution of the universe.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] One can also discover new solutions of the Einstein field equations via the method of orthonormal frames as pioneered by Ellis and MacCallum.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] In this approach, the Einstein field equations are reduced to a set of coupled, nonlinear, ordinary differential equations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] As discussed by Hsu and Wainwright, self-similar solutions to the Einstein field equations are fixed points of the resulting dynamical system.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] New solutions have been discovered using these methods by LeBlanc and Kohli and Haslam.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The nonlinearity of the EFE makes finding exact solutions difficult.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] One way of solving the field equations is to make an approximation, namely, that far from the source(s) of gravitating matter, the gravitational field is very weak and the spacetime approximates that of Minkowski space.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The metric is then written as the sum of the Minkowski metric and a term representing the deviation of the true metric from the Minkowski metric, ignoring higher-power terms.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] This linearization procedure can be used to investigate the phenomena of gravitational radiation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Despite the EFE as written containing the inverse of the metric tensor, they can be arranged in a form that contains the metric tensor in polynomial form and without its inverse.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] Substituting this expression of the inverse of the metric into the equations then multiplying both sides by a suitable power of $\det(g)$ to eliminate it from the denominator results in polynomial equations in the metric tensor and its first and second derivatives.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/einstein-field-equations] The Einstein–Hilbert action from which the equations are derived can also be written in polynomial form by suitable redefinitions of the fields.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] In general relativity, a **geodesic** generalizes the notion of a "straight line" to curved spacetime.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] Importantly, the world line of a particle free from all external, non-gravitational forces is a particular type of geodesic.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] In other words, a freely moving or falling particle always moves along a geodesic.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] In general relativity, gravity can be regarded as not a force but a consequence of a curved spacetime geometry where the source of curvature is the stress–energy tensor (representing matter, for instance).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] Thus, for example, the path of a planet orbiting a star is the projection of a geodesic of the curved four-dimensional (4-D) spacetime geometry around the star onto three-dimensional (3-D) space.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] Greek indices may take the values: 0, 1, 2, 3 and the summation convention is used for repeated indices $\alpha$ and $\beta$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] The quantity on the left-hand-side of the sum in this equation is the acceleration of a particle, so this equation is analogous to Newton's laws of motion, which likewise provide formulae for the acceleration of a particle.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] The Christoffel symbols are functions of the four spacetime coordinates and so are independent of the velocity or acceleration or other characteristics of a test particle whose motion is described by the geodesic equation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] So far the geodesic equation of motion has been written in terms of a scalar parameter *s*.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] It can alternatively be written in terms of the time coordinate, $t\equiv x^{0}$ (here we have used the triple bar to signify a definition).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] This formulation of the geodesic equation of motion can be useful for computer calculations and to compare General Relativity with Newtonian Gravity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] It is straightforward to derive this form of the geodesic equation of motion from the form which uses proper time as a parameter using the chain rule.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] Notice that both sides of this last equation vanish when the mu index is set to zero.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] Here the Latin index *n* takes the values [1,2,3].
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] This equation simply means that all test particles at a particular place and time will have the same acceleration, which is a well-known feature of Newtonian gravity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] For example, everything floating around in the International Space Station will undergo roughly the same acceleration due to gravity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] Physicist Steven Weinberg has presented a derivation of the geodesic equation of motion directly from the equivalence principle.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] The first step in such a derivation is to suppose that a free falling particle does not accelerate in the neighborhood of a point-event with respect to a freely falling coordinate system ( $X^{\mu }$ ).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] Setting $T\equiv X^{0}$ , we have the following equation that is locally applicable in free fall: ${d^{2}X^{\mu } \over dT^{2}}=0.$ The next step is to employ the multi-dimensional chain rule.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] This completes our derivation, since the proper time is defined as the local time at a point that follows the line of motion in question (in this case the geodesic line of a free falling particle).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] Let us continue in order to derive the equations using the coordinate time as parameter.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] Then the first derivative of *x*0 with respect to *t* is one and the second derivative is zero.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] The geodesic equation of motion can alternatively be derived using the concept of parallel transport.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] We can (and this is the most common technique) derive the geodesic equation via the action principle.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] Consider the case of trying to find a geodesic between two timelike-separated events.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] There is a negative sign inside the square root because the curve must be timelike.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] To get the geodesic equation we must vary this action.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] To do this let us parameterize this action with respect to a parameter $\lambda$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] We can now go ahead and vary this action with respect to the curve $x^{\mu }$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] Albert Einstein believed that the geodesic equation of motion can be derived from the field equations for empty space, i.e. from the fact that the Ricci curvature vanishes.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] Both physicists and philosophers have often repeated the assertion that the geodesic equation can be obtained from the field equations to describe the motion of a gravitational singularity, but this claim remains disputed.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] According to David Malament, “Though the geodesic principle can be recovered as theorem in general relativity, it is not a consequence of Einstein’s equation (or the conservation principle) alone.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] Other assumptions are needed to derive the theorems in question.” Less controversial is the notion that the field equations determine the motion of a fluid or dust, as distinguished from the motion of a point-singularity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] In deriving the geodesic equation from the equivalence principle, it was assumed that particles in a local inertial coordinate system are not accelerating.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] However, in real life, the particles may be charged, and therefore may be accelerating locally in accordance with the Lorentz force.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] These last three equations can be used as the starting point for the derivation of an equation of motion in General Relativity, instead of assuming that acceleration is zero in free fall.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] Because the Minkowski tensor is involved here, it becomes necessary to introduce something called the *metric tensor* in General Relativity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] The metric tensor *g* is symmetric, and locally reduces to the Minkowski tensor in free fall.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] This last equation signifies that the particle is moving along a timelike geodesic; massless particles like the photon instead follow null geodesics (replace −1 with zero on the right-hand side of the last equation).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] The letter *g* with superscripts refers to the inverse of the metric tensor.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] In General Relativity, indices of tensors are lowered and raised by contraction with the metric tensor or its inverse, respectively.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] A geodesic between two events can also be described as the curve joining those two events which has a stationary interval (4-dimensional "length").
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] *Stationary* here is used in the sense in which that term is used in the calculus of variations, namely, that the interval along the curve varies minimally among curves that are nearby to the geodesic.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] In simply connected Minkowski space there is only one geodesic that connects any given pair of events, and for a time-like geodesic, this is the curve with the longest proper time between the two events.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] In curved spacetime, it is possible for a pair of widely separated events to have more than one time-like geodesic between them.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] In such instances, the proper times along several geodesics will not in general be the same.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] For some geodesics in such instances, it is possible for a curve that connects the two events and is nearby to the geodesic to have either a longer or a shorter proper time than the geodesic.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] For a space-like geodesic through two events, there are always nearby curves which go through the two events that have either a longer or a shorter proper length than the geodesic, even in Minkowski space.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] In Minkowski space, the geodesic will be a straight line.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] This is just one step away from the geodesic equation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] If the parameter *s* is chosen to be affine, then the right side of the above equation vanishes (because $U_{\nu }U^{\nu }$ is constant).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] The geodesic equation can be alternatively derived from the autoparallel transport of curves.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] The derivation is based on the lectures given by Frederic P.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] Schuller at the We-Heraeus International Winter School on Gravity & Light.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] Let $(M,O,A,\nabla )$ be a smooth manifold with connection and $\gamma$ be a curve on the manifold.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] The curve is said to be autoparallely transported if and only if $\nabla _{v_{\gamma }}v_{\gamma }=0$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/geodesics-in-general-relativity] The first term can be simplified to ${\ddot {\gamma }}^{m}{\frac {\partial }{\partial x^{m}}}$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Gravitational waves transport energy as **gravitational radiation**, a form of radiant energy similar to electromagnetic radiation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Newton's law of universal gravitation, part of classical mechanics, does not provide for their existence, instead asserting that gravity has instantaneous effect everywhere.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Gravitational waves therefore stand as an important relativistic phenomenon that is absent from Newtonian physics.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Gravitational-wave astronomy has the advantage that, unlike electromagnetic radiation, gravitational waves are not affected by intervening matter.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Sources that can be studied this way include binary star systems composed of white dwarfs, neutron stars, and black holes; events such as supernovae; and the formation of the early universe shortly after the Big Bang.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The first indirect evidence for the existence of gravitational waves came in 1974 from the observed orbital decay of the Hulse–Taylor binary pulsar, which matched the decay predicted by general relativity for energy lost to gravitational radiation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In 1993, Russell Alan Hulse and Joseph Hooton Taylor Jr. received the Nobel Prize in Physics for this discovery.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The first direct observation of gravitational waves was made in September 2015, when a signal generated by the merger of two black holes was received by the LIGO gravitational wave detectors in Livingston, Louisiana, and in Hanford, Washington.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The 2017 Nobel Prize in Physics was subsequently awarded to Rainer Weiss, Kip Thorne and Barry Barish for their role in the direct detection of gravitational waves.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In Albert Einstein's general theory of relativity, gravity is treated as a phenomenon resulting from the curvature of spacetime, which is caused by the presence of mass.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] If the masses move, the curvature of spacetime changes; and if the motion is not spherically symmetric, it can emit propagating curvature disturbances—i.e., gravitational waves—which radiate outward at the speed of light.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] A passing gravitational wave alters the relative separation of freely falling masses, reflecting a disturbance in local spacetime curvature.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The separation varies in a pattern that mirrors the waveform of the disturbance.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The magnitude of this effect is inversely proportional to the distance (not distance squared) from the source.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Inspiraling binary neutron stars are predicted to be a powerful source of gravitational waves as they coalesce, due to the very large acceleration of their masses as they orbit close to one another.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] However, due to the astronomical distances to these sources, the effects when measured on Earth are predicted to be very small, having strains of less than 1 part in 1020.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Scientists demonstrate the existence of these waves with highly-sensitive detectors at multiple observation sites.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] As of 2012, the LIGO and Virgo observatories were the most sensitive detectors, operating at resolutions of about one part in 5×1022.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The Japanese detector KAGRA was completed in 2019; its first joint detection with LIGO and VIRGO was reported in 2021.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Another European ground-based detector, the Einstein Telescope, is under development.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] A space-based observatory, the Laser Interferometer Space Antenna (LISA), is also being developed by the European Space Agency.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Gravitational waves do not strongly interact with matter in the way that electromagnetic radiation does.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] This allows for the observation of events involving exotic objects in the distant universe that cannot be observed with more traditional means such as optical telescopes or radio telescopes; accordingly, gravitational wave astronomy gives new insights into the workings of the universe.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In particular, gravitational waves could be of interest to cosmologists as they offer a possible way of observing the very early universe.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] This is not possible with conventional astronomy, since before recombination the universe was opaque to electromagnetic radiation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Precise measurements of gravitational waves will also allow scientists to test more thoroughly the general theory of relativity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In principle, gravitational waves can exist at any frequency.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Very low frequency waves can be detected using pulsar timing arrays.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In this technique, the timing of approximately 100 pulsars spread widely across the Milky Way is monitored over the course of years.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Detectable changes in the arrival time of their signals can result from passing gravitational waves generated by merging supermassive black holes (SMBH) with wavelengths measured in light-years.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] These timing changes can be used to locate the source of the waves.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Using this technique, astronomers have discovered the 'hum' of various SMBH mergers occurring in the universe.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Stephen Hawking and Werner Israel list different frequency bands for gravitational waves that could plausibly be detected, ranging from 10−7 Hz up to 1011 Hz.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The speed of gravitational waves in the general theory of relativity is equal to the *speed of light* in vacuum, c.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Within the theory of special relativity, the constant c is not only about light; instead it is the highest possible speed for any interaction in nature.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Formally, c is a conversion factor for changing the unit of time to the unit of space.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] This makes it the only speed which does not depend either on the motion of an observer or a source of light and/or gravity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Thus, the speed of "light" is also the speed of gravitational waves, and, further, the speed of any massless particle.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In August 2017, the LIGO and Virgo detectors received a gravitational wave signal, GW170817, at nearly the same time as gamma ray satellites and optical telescopes received signals from its source in galaxy NGC 4993, about 130 million light years away.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] This measurement constrained the experimental difference between the speed of gravitational waves and light to be smaller than one part in 1015.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The possibility of gravitational waves and that those might travel at the speed of light was discussed in 1893 by Oliver Heaviside, using the analogy between the inverse-square law of gravitation and the electrostatic force.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In 1915 Einstein published his general theory of relativity, a complete relativistic theory of gravitation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] He conjectured, like Poincaré, that the equation would produce gravitational waves, but, as he mentions in a letter to Schwarzschild in February 1916, these could not be similar to electromagnetic waves.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Electromagnetic waves can be produced by dipole motion, requiring both a positive and a negative charge.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Gravitation has no equivalent to negative charge.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Einstein continued to work through the complexity of the equations of general relativity to find an alternative wave model.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] However, the nature of Einstein's approximations led many (including Einstein himself) to doubt the result.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In 1922, Arthur Eddington showed that two of Einstein's types of waves were artifacts of the coordinate system he used, and could be made to propagate at any speed by choosing appropriate coordinates, leading Eddington to jest that they "propagate at the speed of thought".
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] This also cast doubt on the physicality of the third (transverse–transverse) type that Eddington showed always propagate at the speed of light regardless of coordinate system.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In 1936, Einstein and Nathan Rosen submitted a paper to *Physical Review* in which they claimed gravitational waves could not exist in the full general theory of relativity because any such solution of the field equations would have a singularity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The journal sent their manuscript to be reviewed by Howard P.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Robertson, who anonymously reported that the singularities in question were simply the harmless coordinate singularities of the employed cylindrical coordinates.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Einstein, who was unfamiliar with the concept of peer review, angrily withdrew the manuscript, never to publish in *Physical Review* again.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Nonetheless, his assistant Leopold Infeld, who had been in contact with Robertson, convinced Einstein that the criticism was correct, and the paper was rewritten with the opposite conclusion and published elsewhere.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In 1956, Felix Pirani remedied the confusion caused by the use of various coordinate systems by rephrasing the gravitational waves in terms of the manifestly observable Riemann curvature tensor.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] At the time, Pirani's work was overshadowed by the community's focus on a different question: whether gravitational waves could transmit energy.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] This matter was settled by a thought experiment proposed by Richard Feynman during the first "GR" conference at Chapel Hill in 1957.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In short, his argument known as the "sticky bead argument" notes that if one takes a rod with beads then the effect of a passing gravitational wave would be to move the beads along the rod; friction would then produce heat, implying that the passing wave had done work.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Shortly after, Hermann Bondi published a detailed version of the "sticky bead argument".
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] This later led to a series of articles (1959 to 1989) by Bondi and Pirani that established the existence of plane wave solutions for gravitational waves.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Paul Dirac further postulated the existence of gravitational waves, declaring them to have "physical significance" in his 1959 lecture at the Lindau Meetings.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Further, it was Dirac who predicted gravitational waves with a well-defined energy density in 1964.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] After the Chapel Hill conference, Joseph Weber started designing and building the first gravitational wave detectors now known as Weber bars.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] These doubts were strengthened when, by the mid-1970s, repeated experiments from other groups building their own Weber bars across the globe failed to find any signals, and by the late 1970s consensus was that Weber's results were spurious.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In the same period, the first indirect evidence of gravitational waves was discovered.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In 1974, Russell Alan Hulse and Joseph Hooton Taylor, Jr. discovered the first binary pulsar, which earned them the 1993 Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Pulsar timing observations over the next decade showed a gradual decay of the orbital period of the Hulse–Taylor pulsar that matched the loss of energy and angular momentum in gravitational radiation predicted by general relativity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] This indirect detection of gravitational waves motivated further searches, despite Weber's discredited result.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Some groups continued to improve Weber's original concept, while others pursued the detection of gravitational waves using laser interferometers.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The idea of using a laser interferometer for this seems to have been floated independently by various people, including M.E.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The first prototypes were developed in the 1970s by Robert L.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In the decades that followed, ever more sensitive instruments were constructed, culminating in the construction of GEO600, LIGO, and Virgo.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] After years of producing null results, improved detectors became operational in 2015.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] On 11 February 2016, the LIGO-Virgo collaborations announced the first observation of gravitational waves, from a signal (dubbed GW150914) detected at 09:50:45 GMT on 14 September 2015 of two black holes with masses of 29 and 36 solar masses merging about 1.3 billion light-years away.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] During the final fraction of a second of the merger, it released more than 50 times the power of all the stars in the observable universe combined.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The signal increased in frequency from 35 to 250 Hz over 10 cycles (5 orbits) as it rose in strength for a period of 0.2 second.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The mass of the new merged black hole was 62 solar masses.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Energy equivalent to three solar masses was emitted as gravitational waves.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The signal was seen by both LIGO detectors in Livingston and Hanford, with a time difference of 7 milliseconds due to the angle between the two detectors and the source.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The signal came from the Southern Celestial Hemisphere, in the rough direction of (but much farther away than) the Magellanic Clouds.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The confidence level of this being an observation of gravitational waves was 99.99994%.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] A year earlier, the BICEP2 collaboration claimed that they had detected the imprint of gravitational waves in the cosmic microwave background.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] However, they were later forced to retract this result.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In 2017, the Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded to Rainer Weiss, Kip Thorne and Barry Barish for their role in the detection of gravitational waves.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In 2023, results from pulsar timing arrays were announced suggesting evidence of a gravitational wave background.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Complex analysis of radio observations over 15 years of 67 pulsars showed correlations that matches the Hellings-Downs curve, consistent with a stochastic gravitational wave background.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Similar results are published by European Pulsar Timing Array, who claimed a $3\sigma$ -significance.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The frequency dependence of this background radiation differs from models of the expected source, merging supermassive black hole binaries and other sources cannot yet be ruled out.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Gravitational waves are constantly passing Earth; however, even the strongest have a minuscule effect since their sources are generally at a great distance.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] This tiny effect from even extreme gravitational waves makes them observable on Earth only with the most sophisticated detectors.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The effects of a passing gravitational wave, in an extremely exaggerated form, can be visualized by imagining a perfectly flat region of spacetime with a group of motionless test particles lying in a plane, e.g., the surface of a computer screen.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] As a gravitational wave passes through the particles along a line perpendicular to the plane of the particles, i.e., following the observer's line of vision into the screen, the particles will follow the distortion in spacetime, oscillating in a "cruciform" manner, as shown in the animations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The area enclosed by the test particles does not change and there is no motion along the direction of propagation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The oscillations depicted in the animation are exaggerated for the purpose of discussion – in reality a gravitational wave has a very small amplitude (as formulated in linearized gravity).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] However, they help illustrate the kind of oscillations associated with gravitational waves as produced by a pair of masses in a circular orbit.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In this case the amplitude of the gravitational wave is constant, but its plane of polarization changes or rotates at twice the orbital rate, so the time-varying gravitational wave size, or 'periodic spacetime strain', exhibits a variation as shown in the animation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] If the orbit of the masses is elliptical then the gravitational wave's amplitude also varies with time according to Einstein's quadrupole formula.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] The speed, wavelength, and frequency of a gravitational wave are related by the equation *c* = *λf*, just like the equation for a light wave.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] For example, the animations shown here oscillate roughly once every two seconds.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] This would correspond to a frequency of 0.5 Hz, and a wavelength of about 600 000 km, or 47 times the diameter of the Earth.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In the above example, it is assumed that the wave is linearly polarized with a "plus" polarization, written *h*+.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Polarization of a gravitational wave is just like polarization of a light wave except that the polarizations of a gravitational wave are 45 degrees apart, as opposed to 90 degrees.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] In particular, in a "cross"-polarized gravitational wave, *h*×, the effect on the test particles would be basically the same, but rotated by 45 degrees, as shown in the second animation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Just as with light polarization, the polarizations of gravitational waves may also be expressed in terms of circularly polarized waves.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/gravitational-wave] Gravitational waves are polarized because of the nature of their source.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] A primary goal of numerical relativity is to study spacetimes whose exact form is not known.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] The spacetimes so found computationally can either be fully dynamical, stationary or static and may contain matter fields or vacuum.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] In the case of stationary and static solutions, numerical methods may also be used to study the stability of the equilibrium spacetimes.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] In the case of dynamical spacetimes, the problem may be divided into the initial value problem and the evolution, each requiring different methods.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] Numerical relativity is applied to many areas, such as cosmological models, critical phenomena, perturbed black holes and neutron stars, and the coalescence of black holes and neutron stars, for example.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] In any of these cases, Einstein's equations can be formulated in several ways that allow us to evolve the dynamics.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] While Cauchy methods have received a majority of the attention, characteristic and Regge calculus based methods have also been used.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] All of these methods begin with a snapshot of the gravitational fields on some hypersurface, the initial data, and evolve these data to neighboring hypersurfaces.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] Like all problems in numerical analysis, careful attention is paid to the stability and convergence of the numerical solutions.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] In this line, much attention is paid to the gauge conditions, coordinates, and various formulations of the Einstein equations and the effect they have on the ability to produce accurate numerical solutions.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] Numerical relativity research is distinct from work on classical field theories as many techniques implemented in these areas are inapplicable in relativity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] Many facets are however shared with large scale problems in other computational sciences like computational fluid dynamics, electromagnetics, and solid mechanics.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] Numerical relativists often work with applied mathematicians and draw insight from numerical analysis, scientific computation, partial differential equations, and geometry among other mathematical areas of specialization.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] Albert Einstein published the theory of general relativity in 1915.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] It, like the earlier theory of special relativity, described space and time as a unified spacetime subject to what are now known as the Einstein field equations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] These form a set of coupled nonlinear partial differential equations (PDEs).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] After more than 100 years since the first publication of the theory, relatively few closed-form solutions are known for the field equations, and, of those, most are cosmological solutions that assume special symmetry to reduce the complexity of the equations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] The field of numerical relativity emerged from the desire to construct and study more general solutions to the field equations by approximately solving the Einstein equations numerically.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] A necessary precursor to such attempts was a decomposition of spacetime back into separated space and time.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] This was first published by Richard Arnowitt, Stanley Deser, and Charles W.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] Misner in the late 1950s in what has become known as the ADM formalism.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] At the time that ADM published their original paper, computer technology would not have supported numerical solution to their equations on any problem of any substantial size.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] The first documented attempt to solve the Einstein field equations numerically appears to be by S.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] Lindquist in 1964, followed soon thereafter by Larry Smarr and by K.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] These early attempts were focused on evolving Misner data in axisymmetry (also known as "2+1 dimensions").
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] At around the same time Tsvi Piran wrote the first code that evolved a system with gravitational radiation using a cylindrical symmetry.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] In this calculation Piran has set the foundation for many of the concepts used today in evolving ADM equations, like "free evolution" versus "constrained evolution", which deal with the fundamental problem of treating the constraint equations that arise in the ADM formalism.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] Applying symmetry reduced the computational and memory requirements associated with the problem, allowing the researchers to obtain results on the supercomputers available at the time.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] The first realistic calculations of rotating collapse were carried out in the early 1980s by Richard Stark and Tsvi Piran in which the gravitational wave forms resulting from formation of a rotating black hole were calculated for the first time.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] For nearly 20 years following the initial results, there were fairly few other published results in numerical relativity, probably due to the lack of sufficiently powerful computers to address the problem.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] In the late 1990s, the Binary Black Hole Grand Challenge Alliance successfully simulated a head-on binary black hole collision.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] As a post-processing step the group computed the event horizon for the spacetime.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] This result still required imposing and exploiting axisymmetry in the calculations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] Some of the first documented attempts to solve the Einstein equations in three dimensions were focused on a single Schwarzschild black hole, which is described by a static and spherically symmetric solution to the Einstein field equations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] One of the earliest groups to attempt to simulate this solution was Peter Anninos *et al.* in 1995.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] In the years that followed, not only did computers become more powerful, but also various research groups developed alternate techniques to improve the efficiency of the calculations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] With respect to black hole simulations specifically, two techniques were devised to avoid problems associated with the existence of physical singularities in the solutions to the equations: (1) Excision, and (2) the "puncture" method.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] In addition the Lazarus group developed techniques for using early results from a short-lived simulation solving the nonlinear ADM equations, in order to provide initial data for a more stable code based on linearized equations derived from perturbation theory.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] More generally, adaptive mesh refinement techniques, already used in computational fluid dynamics were introduced to the field of numerical relativity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] In the excision technique, which was first proposed in the late 1990s, a portion of a spacetime inside of the event horizon surrounding the singularity of a black hole is simply not evolved.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] In theory this should not affect the solution to the equations outside of the event horizon because of the principle of causality and properties of the event horizon (i.e. nothing physical inside the black hole can influence any of the physics outside the horizon).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] Thus if one simply does not solve the equations inside the horizon one should still be able to obtain valid solutions outside.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] One "excises" the interior by imposing ingoing boundary conditions on a boundary surrounding the singularity but inside the horizon.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] While the implementation of excision has been very successful, the technique has two minor problems.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] The first is that one has to be careful about the coordinate conditions.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] While physical effects cannot propagate from inside to outside, coordinate effects could.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] For example, if the coordinate conditions were elliptical, coordinate changes inside could instantly propagate out through the horizon.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] This then means that one needs hyperbolic type coordinate conditions with characteristic velocities less than that of light for the propagation of coordinate effects (e.g., using harmonic coordinates coordinate conditions).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] The second problem is that as the black holes move, one must continually adjust the location of the excision region to move with the black hole.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] The excision technique was developed over several years including the development of new gauge conditions that increased stability and work that demonstrated the ability of the excision regions to move through the computational grid.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] The first stable, long-term evolution of the orbit and merger of two black holes using this technique was published in 2005.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] In the puncture method the solution is factored into an analytical part, which contains the singularity of the black hole, and a numerically constructed part, which is then singularity free.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] This is a generalization of the Brill-Lindquist prescription for initial data of black holes at rest and can be generalized to the Bowen-York prescription for spinning and moving black hole initial data.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] Until 2005, all published usage of the puncture method required that the coordinate position of all punctures remain fixed during the course of the simulation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] In 2005, a group of researchers demonstrated for the first time the ability to allow punctures to move through the coordinate system, thus eliminating some of the earlier problems with the method.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] This allowed accurate long-term evolutions of black holes.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] 2005 was named the "*annus mirabilis*" of numerical relativity, 100 years after the *annus mirabilis* papers of special relativity (1905).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] The Lazarus project (1998–2005) was developed as a post-Grand Challenge technique to extract astrophysical results from short lived full numerical simulations of binary black holes.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] It combined approximation techniques before (post-Newtonian trajectories) and after (perturbations of single black holes) with full numerical simulations attempting to solve Einstein's field equations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] All previous attempts to numerically integrate in supercomputers the Hilbert-Einstein equations describing the gravitational field around binary black holes led to software failure before a single orbit was completed.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] Adaptive mesh refinement (AMR) as a numerical method has roots that go well beyond its first application in the field of numerical relativity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] Mesh refinement first appears in the numerical relativity literature in the 1980s, through the work of Choptuik in his studies of critical collapse of scalar fields.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] The original work was in one dimension, but it was subsequently extended to two dimensions.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] In two dimensions, AMR has also been applied to the study of inhomogeneous cosmologies, and to the study of Schwarzschild black holes.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] The technique has now become a standard tool in numerical relativity and has been used to study the merger of black holes and other compact objects in addition to the propagation of gravitational radiation generated by such astronomical events.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] In the 21st century, hundreds of research papers have been published leading to a wide spectrum of mathematical relativity, gravitational wave, and astrophysical results for the orbiting black hole problem.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] This technique extended to astrophysical binary systems involving neutron stars and black holes, and multiple black holes.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] One of the most surprising predictions is that the merger of two black holes can give the remnant hole a speed of up to 4000 km/s that can allow it to escape from any known galaxy.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/numerical-relativity] The simulations also predict an enormous release of gravitational energy in this merger process, amounting up to 8% of its total rest mass.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] In general relativity, **post-Newtonian expansions** (**PN** **expansions**) are used for finding an approximate solution of Einstein field equations for the metric tensor.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] The approximations are expanded in small parameters that express orders of deviations from Newton's law of universal gravitation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] This allows approximations to Einstein's equations to be made in the case of weak fields.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] Higher-order terms can be added to increase accuracy, but for strong fields sometimes it is preferable to solve the complete equations numerically.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] This method is a common mark of effective field theories.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] In the limit, when the small parameters are equal to 0, the post-Newtonian expansion reduces to Newton's law of gravity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] The post-Newtonian methods require both low speed masses and weak gravitational fields.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] These requirements are fully met in all solar-system tests of general relativity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] The high velocities that generate gravitational radiation or the large fields between binary compact objects like pairs of black holes are not adequately modeled by post-Newtonian expansion.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] Cosmological models are based on different physical assumptions and do not benefit from this approximation method.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] The **post-Newtonian approximations** are expansions in a small parameter, which is the ratio of the velocity of the matter that creates the gravitational field, to the speed of light, which in this case is more precisely called the *speed of gravity*.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] In the limit, when the fundamental speed of gravity becomes infinite, the post-Newtonian expansion reduces to Newton's law of gravity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] A systematic study of post-Newtonian expansions within hydrodynamic approximations was developed by Subrahmanyan Chandrasekhar and his colleagues in the 1960s.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] Another approach is to expand the equations of general relativity in a power series in the deviation of the metric from its value in the absence of gravity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] To this end, one must choose a coordinate system in which the eigenvalues of $h_{\alpha \beta }\eta ^{\beta \gamma }\,$ all have absolute values less than 1.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] Expansions based only on the metric, independently from the speed, are called post-Minkowskian expansions (PM expansions).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] Comparison table of powers used for PN and PM approximations in the case of two non-rotating bodies.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] 0PN corresponds to the case of Newton's theory of gravitation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] 0PM (not shown) corresponds to the Minkowski flat space.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] The first use of a PN expansion (to first order) was made by Albert Einstein in calculating the perihelion precession of Mercury's orbit.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] Today, Einstein's calculation is recognized as a common example of applications of PN expansions, solving the general relativistic two-body problem, which includes the emission of gravitational waves.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] where $\Box$ is the d'Alembert operator, E is a scalar, ${\hat {E}}_{i}$ is a vector and ${\tilde {E}}_{ij}$ is a traceless tensor.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] where H is the Hubble constant and a prime represents differentiation with respect to conformal time $\tau \,$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] Note that in the absence of anisotropic stress, $\Phi =\Psi$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/post-newtonian-expansion] A useful non-linear extension of this is provided by the non-relativistic gravitational fields.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The solution is a useful approximation for describing slowly rotating astronomical objects such as many stars and planets, including Earth and the Sun.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] It was found by Karl Schwarzschild and independently of him by Johannes Droste in 1916.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] According to Birkhoff's theorem, the Schwarzschild metric is the most general spherically symmetric vacuum solution of the Einstein field equations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] A **Schwarzschild black hole** or **static black hole** is a black hole that has neither electric charge nor angular momentum (non-rotating).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] A Schwarzschild black hole is described by the Schwarzschild metric, and cannot be distinguished from any other Schwarzschild black hole except by its mass.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild black hole is characterized by a surrounding spherical boundary, called the event horizon, which is situated at the Schwarzschild radius (⁠ $r_{\text{s}}$ ⁠), often called the radius of a black hole.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The boundary is not a physical surface, and a person who fell through the event horizon (before being torn apart by tidal forces) would not notice any physical surface at that position; it is a mathematical surface which is significant in determining the black hole's properties.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Any non-rotating and non-charged mass that is smaller than its Schwarzschild radius forms a black hole.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The solution of the Einstein field equations is valid for any mass M, so in principle (within the theory of general relativity) a Schwarzschild black hole of any mass could exist if conditions became sufficiently favorable to allow for its formation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] In the vicinity of a Schwarzschild black hole, space curves so much that even light rays are deflected, and very nearby light can be deflected so much that it travels several times around the black hole.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The rotation group $\mathrm {SO} (3)=\mathrm {SO} (E^{3})$ acts on the $E^{3}-O$ or $S^{2}$ factor as rotations around the center O , while leaving the first $\mathbb {R}$ factor unchanged.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild metric is a solution of Einstein's field equations in empty space, meaning that it is valid only *outside* the gravitating body.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] That is, for a spherical body of radius R the solution is valid for $r>R$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] To describe the gravitational field both inside and outside the gravitating body the Schwarzschild solution must be matched with some suitable interior solution at ⁠ $r=R$ ⁠, such as the interior Schwarzschild metric.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild metric has a singularity for *r* = 0, which is an intrinsic curvature singularity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] It also seems to have a singularity on the event horizon *r* = *r*s.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Depending on the point of view, the metric is therefore defined only on the exterior region $r>r_{\text{s}}$ , only on the interior region $r<r_{\text{s}}$ or their disjoint union.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] However, the metric is actually non-singular across the event horizon, as one sees in suitable coordinates (see below).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] For ⁠ $r\gg r_{\text{s}}$ ⁠, the Schwarzschild metric is asymptotic to the standard Lorentz metric on Minkowski space.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] For almost all astrophysical objects, the ratio ${\frac {r_{\text{s}}}{R}}$ is extremely small.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] For example, the Schwarzschild radius $r_{\text{s}}^{({\text{Earth}})}$ of the Earth is roughly 8.9 mm, while the Sun, which is 3.3×105 times as massive has a Schwarzschild radius $r_{\text{s}}^{({\text{Sun}})}$ of approximately 3.0 km.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The ratio becomes large only in close proximity to black holes and other ultra-dense objects such as neutron stars.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The radial coordinate turns out to have physical significance as the "proper distance between two events that occur simultaneously relative to the radially moving geodesic clocks, the two events lying on the same radial coordinate line".
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild solution is analogous to a classical Newtonian theory of gravity that corresponds to the gravitational field around a point particle.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Even at the surface of the Earth, the corrections to Newtonian gravity are only one part in a billion.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] However, this is enough for the metric to be used to correct for gravitational time dilation in the Global Positioning System.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild solution is named in honour of Karl Schwarzschild, who found the exact solution in 1915 and published it in January 1916, a little more than a month after the publication of Einstein's theory of general relativity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] It was the first exact solution of the Einstein field equations other than the trivial flat space solution.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Schwarzschild died shortly after his paper was published, as a result of a disease (thought to be pemphigus) he developed while serving in the German army during World War I.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Johannes Droste in 1916 independently produced the same solution as Schwarzschild, using a simpler, more direct derivation.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] In the early years of general relativity there was a lot of confusion about the nature of the singularities found in the Schwarzschild and other solutions of the Einstein field equations.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] In Schwarzschild's original paper, he put what we now call the event horizon at the origin of his coordinate system.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] In this paper he also introduced what is now known as the Schwarzschild radial coordinate (r in the equations above), as an auxiliary variable.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] In his equations, Schwarzschild was using a different radial coordinate that was zero at the Schwarzschild radius.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] A more complete analysis of the singularity structure was given by David Hilbert in the following year, identifying the singularities both at *r* = 0 and *r* = *r*s.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Although there was general consensus that the singularity at *r* = 0 was a 'genuine' physical singularity, the nature of the singularity at *r* = *r*s remained unclear.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] They, however, did not recognize that their solutions were just coordinate transforms, and in fact used their solution to argue that Einstein's theory was wrong.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] In 1924 Arthur Eddington produced the first coordinate transformation (Eddington–Finkelstein coordinates) that showed that the singularity at *r* = *r*s was a coordinate artifact, although he also seems to have been unaware of the significance of this discovery.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Later, in 1932, Georges Lemaître gave a different coordinate transformation (Lemaître coordinates) to the same effect and was the first to recognize that this implied that the singularity at *r* = *r*s was not physical.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] In 1939 Howard Robertson showed that a free falling observer descending in the Schwarzschild metric would cross the *r* = *r*s singularity in a finite amount of proper time even though this would take an infinite amount of time in terms of coordinate time t.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] In 1950, John Synge produced a paper that showed the maximal analytic extension of the Schwarzschild metric, again showing that the singularity at *r* = *r*s was a coordinate artifact and that it represented two horizons.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] A similar result was later rediscovered by George Szekeres, and independently Martin Kruskal.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The new coordinates nowadays known as Kruskal–Szekeres coordinates were much simpler than Synge's but both provided a single set of coordinates that covered the entire spacetime.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] However, perhaps due to the obscurity of the journals in which the papers of Lemaître and Synge were published their conclusions went unnoticed, with many of the major players in the field including Einstein believing that the singularity at the Schwarzschild radius was physical.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Real progress was made in the 1960s when the mathematically rigorous formulation cast in terms of differential geometry entered the field of general relativity, allowing more exact definitions of what it means for a Lorentzian manifold to be singular.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] This led to definitive identification of the *r* = *r*s singularity in the Schwarzschild metric as an event horizon, i.e., a hypersurface in spacetime that can be crossed in only one direction.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild solution appears to have singularities at *r* = 0 and *r* = *r*s; some of the metric components "blow up" (entail division by zero or multiplication by infinity) at these radii.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Since the Schwarzschild metric is expected to be valid only for those radii larger than the radius R of the gravitating body, there is no problem as long as *R* > *r*s.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] For ordinary stars and planets this is always the case.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] For example, the radius of the Sun is approximately 700000 km, while its Schwarzschild radius is only 3 km.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The singularity at *r* = *r*s divides the Schwarzschild coordinates in two disconnected patches.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The *exterior Schwarzschild solution* with *r* > *r*s is the one that is related to the gravitational fields of stars and planets.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The *interior Schwarzschild solution* with 0 ≤ *r* < *r*s, which contains the singularity at *r* = 0, is completely separated from the outer patch by the singularity at *r* = *r*s.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild coordinates therefore give no physical connection between the two patches, which may be viewed as separate solutions.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The singularity at *r* = *r*s is an illusion however; it is an instance of what is called a *coordinate singularity*.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] As the name implies, the singularity arises from a bad choice of coordinates or coordinate conditions.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Using a different coordinate transformation one can then relate the extended external patch to the inner patch.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] If one asks that the solution be valid for all r one runs into a true physical singularity, or *gravitational singularity*, at the origin.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] To see that this is a true singularity one must look at quantities that are independent of the choice of coordinates.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] At *r* = 0 the curvature becomes infinite, indicating the presence of a singularity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] At this point the metric cannot be extended in a smooth manner (the Kretschmann invariant involves second derivatives of the metric), spacetime itself is then no longer well-defined.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Furthermore, Sbierski showed the metric cannot be extended even in a continuous manner.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] For a long time it was thought that such a solution was non-physical.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] However, a greater understanding of general relativity led to the realization that such singularities were a generic feature of the theory and not just an exotic special case.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild solution, taken to be valid for all *r* > 0, is called a Schwarzschild black hole.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] It is a perfectly valid solution of the Einstein field equations, although (like other black holes) it has rather bizarre properties.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] For *r* < *r*s the Schwarzschild radial coordinate r becomes timelike and the time coordinate t becomes spacelike.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] A curve at constant r is no longer a possible worldline of a particle or observer, not even if a force is exerted to try to keep it there; this occurs because spacetime has been curved so much that the direction of cause and effect (the particle's future light cone) points into the singularity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The surface *r* = *r*s demarcates what is called the *event horizon* of the black hole.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] It represents the point past which light can no longer escape the gravitational field.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Any physical object whose radius R becomes less than or equal to the Schwarzschild radius has undergone gravitational collapse and become a black hole.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The Schwarzschild solution can be expressed in a range of different choices of coordinates besides the Schwarzschild coordinates used above.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Different choices tend to highlight different features of the solution.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The table below shows some popular choices.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] In table above, some shorthand has been introduced for brevity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The speed of light c has been set to one.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The notation $g_{\Omega }=d\theta ^{2}+\sin ^{2}\theta \,d\varphi ^{2}$ is used for the metric of a unit radius 2-dimensional sphere.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Moreover, in each entry *R* and *T* denote alternative choices of radial and time coordinate for the particular coordinates.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Note, the *R* or *T* may vary from entry to entry.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The Kruskal–Szekeres coordinates have the form to which the Belinski–Zakharov transform can be applied.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] This implies that the Schwarzschild black hole is a form of gravitational soliton.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The spatial curvature of the Schwarzschild solution for *r* > *r*s can be visualized as the graphic shows.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Consider a constant time equatorial slice *H* through the Schwarzschild solution by fixing *θ* = ⁠π/2⁠, t = constant, and letting the remaining Schwarzschild coordinates (*r*, *φ*) vary.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Imagine now that there is an additional Euclidean dimension w, which has no physical reality (it is not part of spacetime).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Thus, Flamm's paraboloid is useful for visualizing the spatial curvature of the Schwarzschild metric.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] It should not, however, be confused with a gravity well.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] No ordinary (massive or massless) particle can have a worldline lying on the paraboloid, since all distances on it are spacelike (this is a cross-section at one moment of time, so any particle moving on it would have an infinite velocity).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] A tachyon could have a spacelike worldline that lies entirely on a single paraboloid.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] However, even in that case its geodesic path is not the trajectory one gets through a "rubber sheet" analogy of gravitational well: in particular, if the dimple is drawn pointing upward rather than downward, the tachyon's geodesic path still curves toward the central mass, not away.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] See the gravity well article for more information.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Flamm's paraboloid may be derived as follows.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] A particle orbiting in the Schwarzschild metric can have a stable circular orbit with *r* > 3*r*s.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Circular orbits with r between 1.5*r*s and 3*r*s are unstable, and no circular orbits exist for *r* < 1.5*r*s.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The circular orbit of minimum radius 1.5*r*s corresponds to an orbital velocity approaching the speed of light.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] It is possible for a particle to have a constant value of r between *r*s and 1.5*r*s, but only if some force acts to keep it there.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Noncircular orbits, such as Mercury's, dwell longer at small radii than would be expected in Newtonian gravity.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] This can be seen as a less extreme version of the more dramatic case in which a particle passes through the event horizon and dwells inside it forever.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Intermediate between the case of Mercury and the case of an object falling past the event horizon, there are exotic possibilities such as knife-edge orbits, in which the satellite can be made to execute an arbitrarily large number of nearly circular orbits, after which it flies back outward.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] This is thus the subgroup of the ten-dimensional Poincaré group which takes the time axis (trajectory of the star) to itself.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] It omits the spatial translations (three dimensions) and boosts (three dimensions).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] It retains the time translations (one dimension) and rotations (three dimensions).
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Like the Poincaré group, it has four connected components: the component of the identity; the time reversed component; the spatial inversion component; and the component which is both time reversed and spatially inverted.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] The Ricci curvature scalar and the Ricci curvature tensor are both zero.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] 5.13 in Carroll and imply the other 6 by $R^{\alpha }{}_{\beta \gamma \delta }=g^{\alpha \kappa }g_{\beta \lambda }R^{\lambda }{}_{\kappa \delta \gamma }$ .
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] Components which are obtainable by other symmetries of the Riemann tensor are not displayed.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] To understand the physical meaning of these quantities, it is useful to express the curvature tensor in an orthonormal basis.
[src:general-relativity-numerics/schwarzschild-metric] These results are invariant to any Lorentz boost, thus the components do not change for non-static observers.
